Abstract Factory → creates a family of related products

Abstract factory pattern has creational purpose and provides an interface for creating families of related or dependent objects without specifying their concrete classes. Pattern applies to object and deal with object relationships, which are more dynamic. In contrast to Factory Method, Abstract Factory pattern produces family of types that are related, ie. it has more than one method of types it produces.

When to use
a system should be independent of how its products are created, composed, and represented
a system should be configured with one of multiple families of products
a family of related product objects is designed to be used together
you want to provide a class library of products, and you want to reveal just their interfaces, not their implementations

=======================
class AvailabilityService {
public:
    virtual void checkAvailability() = 0;
    virtual ~AvailabilityService() {}
};

class PricingService {
public:
    virtual void calculatePrice() = 0;
    virtual ~PricingService() {}
};
Step 3 — Concrete Products
Amadeus
class AmadeusAvailability : public AvailabilityService {
public:
    void checkAvailability() override {
        cout << "Amadeus availability\n";
    }
};

class AmadeusPricing : public PricingService {
public:
    void calculatePrice() override {
        cout << "Amadeus pricing\n";
    }
};
Sabre
class SabreAvailability : public AvailabilityService {
public:
    void checkAvailability() override {
        cout << "Sabre availability\n";
    }
};

class SabrePricing : public PricingService {
public:
    void calculatePrice() override {
        cout << "Sabre pricing\n";
    }
};
Step 4 — Abstract Factory
class HotelFactory {
public:
    virtual AvailabilityService* createAvailability() = 0;
    virtual PricingService* createPricing() = 0;
    virtual ~HotelFactory() {}
};
Step 5 — Concrete Factories
class AmadeusFactory : public HotelFactory {
public:
    AvailabilityService* createAvailability() override {
        return new AmadeusAvailability();
    }

    PricingService* createPricing() override {
        return new AmadeusPricing();
    }
};

class SabreFactory : public HotelFactory {
public:
    AvailabilityService* createAvailability() override {
        return new SabreAvailability();
    }

    PricingService* createPricing() override {
        return new SabrePricing();
    }
};
Step 6 — Client Code
int main() {
    HotelFactory* factory = new AmadeusFactory();

    auto availability = factory->createAvailability();
    auto pricing = factory->createPricing();

    availability->checkAvailability();
    pricing->calculatePrice();
}